the infant is immersed in a world of sound in which the characteristic patterns of speech mingle with all the other noises of everyday life, and is surrounded by variously accomplished speakers who provide support in the form both of contextually grounded interpretations of the infant's vocalisations and of demonstrations, or 'attention-directing gestures' (Zukow-Goldring 1997: 221-3), to accompany their own.

