Learning to catch, to climb, or to eat and drink, to cite a few of Sperber's examples (1996: 117), is a matter not of acquiring from an environment representations that satisfy the input conditions of preconstituted modules, but of the formation, within an environment, of the necessary neurological connections, along with attendant features of musculature and anatomy, that establish these various competencies.

