@article{Mckimmie2015,
annote = {Festinger (1957), described dissonance as an intraindividual phenomenon in a social context

Dissonance is conceptualized as an aversive psychological drive state that we are motivated to reduce, much like hunger or thirst (there is some argument about whether dissonance as a drive exists or is merely a useful concept for predicting outcomes; see Kenworthy, Miller, Collins, Read, {\&} Earleywine, 2011)

It is the result of an inconsistency between two or more cognitions – that is, one cognition follows from the opposite of the other.According to Festinger (1957), dissonance can be reduced by changing one of the cognitions or generating new cogni- tions to restore consonance, or by downplaying the importance of the dissonance-arousing cognitions

Group Dissonance:
Stroebe and Diehl's (1981, 1988) studies focused on the dissonance-reducing function of group-related information. Participants were induced to write a counter-attitudinal essay and then were told about the behavior and (sometimes) the attitude of another participant who had been asked to write the same essay.

Stroebe and Diehl (1981) found that under conditions that elicit dissonance (i.e., behaving in a counter-attitudinal manner under conditions of high choice), participants' attitudes became more positive when theywere told that another participant had not written the essay compared towhen told that the other participant hadwritten the essay

Participants' attitudes becamemore positive after writing a counter-attitudinal essay when they were told that the other participant held the opposite attitude to them compared to when told that the other participant held the same attitude as themselves. Stroebe and Diehl interpreted these findings as suggesting that the attitudes and behaviors of others in the immediate social context acted as a social reward and so helped to reduce the need for dissonance reduction via attitude change, functionally much like the financial reward in Festinger and Carlsmith's(1959) study.

Stone,Wiegand, Cooper, and Aronson (1997): In their first study, participants experienced less dissonancewhen they were made mindful of the past behavioral failures of other people (i.e., when the behavior of otherswas the same as participants' own behavior) compared to when they were asked to fo- cus on their own past failures. In essence, when participantswere asked to think about the pres- ence of support for their behavior, they experienced less hypocrisy-induced dissonance

McKimmie et al. (2003): participants were made to feel hypocritical via a biased behavioral checklist. 
asked to think about themselves as individuals or as a member of a group that was either low or high in contextual salience. 

The presence or absence of social support had the greatest effect on attitude change when the shared group membership was made salient. 

Interestingly, the shared group identity also provided an additional avenue for dissonance reduction via reduced group identification when that group did not provide social support. Thus, it appeared that experiencing dissonance in the context of a group changed the arousal and reduction of dissonance. 

A similar conclusion can be drawn from research examining how members of a co-acting group experience dissonance:

DIFFUSION of RESPONSIBILITY
Zanna and Sande (1987) asked participants to write a counter-attitudinal essay that might bring about an aversive outcome. 

Conditions: 3 participants at a time either alone (individual essays) or in a group (one group essay). 

Predicitons: 
1. those acting counter-attitudinally in the group would be able to reduce dissonance by dif- fusing responsibility for the aversive counter-attitudinal behavior to the other group members
2. participants would see the group product as beingmore likely to produce aversive consequences

Results:
as predicted, participants changed their attitudes less in the group condition, but they also thought the group essay would be more persuasive (and so thereforemore likely to produce aversive consequences)

More responsibility more dissonance:
Further, the more the participants thought that the other group members were responsible for the essay, the less they changed their own attitudes. 

Social support (i.e., the co-acting group members), it appears, did not reduce dissonance by introducing consonant cognitions but rather via diffusion of responsibility for the aversive consequences of the counter-attitudinal behavior.

