affected how they responded to the dissonance-inducing request to not play with an attractive toy. 
children from the lower class background derogated the attractive toy to a greater extent than children from the middle class background when the threat to not play with the toy was mild compared to severe.

Robertson and Reicher (1997): norms may reduce dissonancewhen they validate
the counter-attitudinal behavior or when they suggest that attitude–behavior inconsistency is normative. 

Identity contradiction model:
dissonance effects, particularly those in the induced compliance paradigm, were best understood from social identity theory (Tajfel, 1978; Tajfel {\&} Turner, 1979) and self-categorization theory (Turner, Hogg, Oakes, Reicher, {\&}Wetherell, 1987).

Thus, dissonance effectswere cast as being context specific and ref lecting threats to social identity in several different ways.

