The degree to which the contrast between one's own inconsis- tency and another's inconsistency accentuates or attenuates perceptions of self-consistency de- termines the extent of dissonance arousal. 

important social groups provide a comparative context for one'sattitude–behavior discrepancy.

- meta-consistency lowest when there is no support for a specific behavior or attitude. If you are behaving counter-attitudinally and you are told that another person has not performed the same counter-attitudinal behavior (i.e., no social support), then that information strongly suggests that that person is behaving in an attitude-consistent manner.

The diffusion of responsibility paradigm more directly inf luences the level of meta-consistency – members of group working on a joint product are aware that others are also behaving inconsistently (high meta-consistency).

the meta-consistency perspective builds on the self-standards model by explicitly recognizing that group norms can also serve to reduce dissonance through a number of mechanisms.

Is meta-consistency a meta-cognitive or serial thought process? 

meta-cognitive process: likely that actors will be affected either by the information about the consistency of other groupmem- bers' attitudes and behaviors or by the content of those attitudes, behaviors, and associated norms but not both.

serial: The meaning of the attitudes, behaviors, and norms may be considered first, followed by the meta-consistency information if that first step is not successful at reducing dissonance

(Such a possibility suggests that actors are highly motivated to reduce dissonance and actively use social information in multiple ways to attempt to alleviate the experience of dissonance rather than being relatively passive perceivers who are limited by what is initially made salient in the current social context.)

As such, although groups can be a source of dissonance arousal, these additional options for dissonance reduction tip the scales in favor of groups providing an overall benefit in terms of the experience of dissonance. This may be one important reason that individuals seek to belong to groups.

Group Dissonance and the Consistent Perceiver

Group attitudes and behaviors:
groups may create dissonance by introducing new cognitions that are inconsistent with a person's existing cognitions (Festinger).

1. through attitudes of other group members

The effect of groupmembers' attitudes:
(Matz{\&}Wood, 2005): students reported more discomfort when they thought about a group that disagreed with their attitudes. 
They also found in a follow-up study that this effectwas moderated by the level of free choice, which is a standard moderator of dissonance effects.
A final study suggested that group consensus after the initial disagreement was effective at reducing dissonance. 
Interestingly, subsequent research (Matz, Hofstedt, {\&} Wood, 2008) suggests that the effect of group disagreement is somewhat dependent on one's personality. 
Introverts appear to be more susceptible to the effect of group disagreement than extraverts.

2. through behaviors of other group members:

Glasford, Pratto, and Dovidio (2008) termed this intragroup dissonance and adopted a social identity framework (Tajfel, 1978).

groups may create dissonance when there is a discrepancy between a group member's personal values and the behavior of the ingroup, regardless of that individual's role in the group's behavior.

The results of two experiments supported such an idea and also showed that the group membership not only did create dissonance but also did provide strategies for group members to reduce their dissonance.

Group memberswho had an important value violated by the behavior of the group were able to reduce dissonance by either reducing their identification with the group (as in McKimmie et al.'s, 2003 study) or engaging in pro-value activism.

Further evidence that social identity is at the center of intragroup dissonance and that intragroup dissonance is distinct fromcollective guilt can be seen in their subsequent work (Glasford, Dovidio, {\&} Pratto, 2009): higher group identification tended to make group identity enhancement strategies more effective and more likely to be chosen.

Norms as a source of dissonance

"Vicarious dissonance"

Norton, Monin, Cooper, and Hogg (2003):

first study found that participants changed their attitudes to apparently reduce dissonance when participants heard about another student who had acted inconsistently, but only when the other student came from the same group as participants, and participants themselves identified with that group

second study showed that attitude change was due to vicarious dissonance and not simply due to being persuaded by the other student's counter-attitudinal speech (see also Monin, Norton, Cooper, {\&} Hogg, 2004).

A third study showed that the effect was moderated by the standard moderators of cognitive dissonance – freedom of choice and the presence of aversive consequences.

Thus, groups appear to create dissonance in the absence of attitude–behavior inconsistency
