participants in the present study experienced little dissonance discomfort when they were given low choice about taking an opposing position in the group or when they freely disagreed and then were encouraged to self-affirm important self-attributes

In summary, the first two studies provide support for our
group-y perspective on dissonance. They indicate that dissonance arises from inconsistencies grounded in interpersonal interaction, much as past research with individual-level paradigms has dem- onstrated that dissonance arises from intrapersonal inconsistencies, especially from individual's counterattitudinal behavior.

