focus on longer-term mood rather than fleeting emotion: Mood refers to a “background” emotional state that “rises and dissipates slowly”

Mood refers to a “background” emotional state that “rises and dissipates slowly” (Beedie, Terry, {\&} Lane, 2005, p. 871)

According to a number of studies, people think differently in a euphoric versus dysphoric mood (for a review, see Clore {\&} Huntsinger, 2007)

In a euphoric mood, people adopt a more global, schematic view. In other words, they tend to look at the “big picture.” In contrast, people in a dysphoric mood tend to be more non-schematic and details-oriented.

Bless et al. (1996) found that participants with an induced positive mood were more likely to falsely recognize an item from a story (when the stimulus is conceptually similar but a different word) than those in a negative mood. Participants in a positive mood appeared to fall back on general semantic knowledge whereas those in a negative mood remembered the details better

Gasper and Clore (2002) asked their participants to draw/ classify pictures they had seen before, and found that participants with an induced positive mood focused on the global characteristics at the expense of the details, while those in a negative mood did the opposite.

Beukeboom and Semin (2005) found the same results in a paradigm where they asked participants to choose appropriate phrases to describe behaviors: those in a good mood thought more about “why” a behavior occurred, and those in a bad mood thought more about “how” a behavior occurred.

Frederickson and Branigan (2005) confirmed the broadening effect of positive mood in a study where they asked participants to choose which image was the most similar to a previous one. The two choices were appropriate either for a global view (overall shape) or a detailed view (component parts of the overall shape). Those in a good mood chose overall shape more often.

Mood affects performance in a variety of domains outside of religion. For example, in
sports performance (Stevens, 2006) and school examinations (Thelwell, Lane, {\&} Weston, 2007), a person's background mood feeds into an assessment of the task (how well they can perform according to expectations) to produce a coping strategy.

Expertise:
The extent of a person's expertise makes a difference here too. If a task overwhelms a person's abilities, and success appears unlikely, then the mood might become depressed and performance might suffer; but if the task seems doable, then mood might contribute to success (for a discussion, see Stevens, 2006; Thelwell et al., 2007)

However, Pe, Tan, and Heller (2008) failed to find an advantage of mood in playing the TOH (and another game), although game success did improve mood afterward. Similarly, Spering, Wagener, and Funke (2005) failed to find an advantage of good mood in a complicated business simulation game.

