External variables that are to effectively influence the functioning of the Positive Group Affect Spiral need to target its driving mechanisms (i.e., affective sharing and affective similarity-attraction) in order change the causal relationships between positive group affective similarity and group relationship quality and to either decelerate or accelerate the spiraling process.

Charismatic leadership
Managing subordinates' affect is often considered a crucial leadership task (Humphrey, 2002), particularly in the context of charismatic leadership (e.g., Ashkanasy {\&} Tse, 2000; Bass, 1988 Wasiliewski, 1985).

Charismatic leaders arouse followers emotionally, evoking positive affective reactions by communicating an emotionally captivating vision (McColl-Kennedy {\&} Anderson, 2002; Shamir, House, {\&} Arthur, 1993)

instill pride, faith, and respect in followers by acting as optimistic and confident role models and by emphasizing the relevance of collective (i.e., group and organizational) goals 

Such leaders harness followers' positive feelings by focusing these affective reactions on themselves (e.g., liking and admiration) or on the organization and its aspirations (e.g., enthusiasm and determination; Ashforth{\&} Humphrey, 1995; Avolio{\&}Bass, 1988; Howell{\&}Shamir, 2005).

Followers are likely to express these positive feelings in a particularly open and pronounced manner, because such expressions are positively regarded and supported by the leader

charismatic leadership may enhance the attractiveness of followers' positive affective expressions beyond the effects of mere affective similarity-attraction.

charismatic leadership has been shown to enhance groups' affective
climate (Pirola-Merlo, Hartel, Mann, {\&} Hirst, 2002)

charismatic influences need not remain limited to groups' formal leaders (Kelly
{\&} Barsade, 2001), even though higher-power individuals may be particularly likely to influence others' moods and emotions (Anderson et al., 2003)

Charisma constitutes a personal base of power which does not rely on formal, hierarchical prerequisites (House, 1991)

Largely irrespective of their hierarchical positioning, charismatic individuals have been suggested and found to influence others' affect, thus functioning as ‘mood carriers' (Totterdell et al., 1998, p. 1514) who may provoke and facilitate affective sharing and affective similarity-attraction through their engaging appeal, emotional expressiveness, and collective orientation (cf. Bono{\&}Ilies, 2006;Hatfield et al., 1992; Shamir et al., 1993)

Charismatic group membersmay thus emerge as informal leaderswith profound influences on othermembers' affect and the expressions thereof (Pescosolido, 2002), potentially shaping the functioning of the Positive Group Affect Spiral as described above

