followers. They may share charismatic relations only with some followers but not with others, depending, for example, on leaders' efforts to treat all followers consistently and on individual followers' skill, values, and orientations (Klein {\&} House, 1995)

For instance, mechanisms of affective sharing may suffer from leaders' unequal treatment of their followers, as only some followers have favorable, charismatic relations with the leader while others do not. Such inconsistency in charismatic leadership may diminish the quality of work groups' social environments and decrease followers' well-being, commitment, and morale (Bliese {\&} Britt, 2001; Bliese {\&} Halverson, 1998; Cole {\&} Bedeian, 2007).

‘[w]hen followers are divided in their loyalty and enthusiasm for a common leader but must work closely together, intragroup conflict and resentment appear likely' (p. 192–193; see also Dansereau, Graen, {\&} Haga, 1975; Graen{\&}Uhl-Bien, 1995)

Leaders' differential treatment of their followers may clearly emphasize interpersonal dissimilarities (e.g., rendering some group members ‘second-class followers'; Klein {\&} House, 1995, p. 192), diminishing the salience of transient affective reactions for producing similarity-attraction effects

Also, those group members who do not share charismatic relations with the leader may find little appeal in his or her vision (Waldman{\&}Yammarino, 1999)

Proposition 4b. Inconsistency in charismatic leadership towards group members diminishes, while consistency in charismatic leadership facilitates the functioning of the Positive Group Affect Spiral.


