Nonaggregativity:
Wimsatt (1986) equated emergence with nonaggregativity. Most social properties are not aggregative and thus are emergent

Aggregative properties meet four criteria, and most social properties do not satisfy them:
1. the system property is not a product of the way the system is organized; the parts are intersubstitutable without affecting the system property
In social systems, individualists and collectivists alike agree that individuals and subsystems are not intersubstitutable because the network of relationships between individuals is significant
2. an aggregative property should remain qualitatively similar under addition or removal of a part from the system
