Elaborated Social Identity Model of crowd behavior (ESIM; Drury {\&} Reicher, 2005, 2009)
the shift from “me” to “we” means a greater commitment and loyalty to the group, which is now seen more like “self” than as “other.”

According to the ESIM, the changes in self-categorization resulting from participation in a collective movement can account for the transformation of an aggregate of individuals into a psychologically unified crowd with social cohesion. 

shared emotions play a key role in collective gatherings. Social identification results from a “hot” emotional process that complements the cognitive self- categorization

Collective Gatherings and Shared Flow
gatherings or rituals as “affordances that a society offers to its members in order to allow them to meet optimal experiences under socially desirable forms” (Csikszentmih{\'{a}}lyi 1990, p. 432)

Interviews with athletes revealed that in team sports, unison movements, and shared focus of attention are critical to the experience of flow (Schiepe-Tiska {\&} Engerser, 2011)

Hypotheses

