@article{Wang2009,
abstract = {This research adopts methodological relationalism as its conceptual framework. The Collection of Sages' Maxims (CSM) is used as the basic data to derive the cultural norms. Based on these norms, eight parameters (prs) are derived with 24 metaperception components of filial piety and fraternal submission (FPFS)-based interpersonal loyalty. These FPFS loyalty (FPFSL) metaperception components as third-eye party are seen to be highly sensitive and vigilant with regard to transgressions of the cultural maxim-based norms. Then these metaperception components are supposed to help prompt the transgressor to generate emotions of guilt and shame in his/her reflection.},
annote = {Chinese maxims of guilt and shame

guilt and shame conceived and experienced differently in different cultures

Guilt and shame in China: Bedford, 2004; Ho, Fu {\&} Ng, 2004; Hong, 2004

Emotions such as guilt and shame arise from reflective judgments about the transgression of cultural norms and are closely connected with ‘the evaluative standards jointly set by cultural ideals and personal transformations of them' (Hong, 2004, p. 60）

the responsibility of helping keep the stability of the state through developing the individual's awareness of loyalty in interpersonal relationships in general and toward the ruler in particular (will this lead to a bias in responses in order to keep harmony? will the variance of "individual" responses diminish? How to ilicit the responses I am looking for re social bonding and dissonance?)



This cultivation of personhood would lead to the regulation of families, in turn to the regulation of states, and ultimately to the regulation of the whole empire




These evaluative standards are fundamentally fostered by and embedded in cultural norms.

CHINA: human self–other relational morality replaces religion (Bodde, 1946; Liang, 1998).

loyalty-based metaperception

filial piety and fraternal submission loyalty (FPFSL) metaperception

(1) a relational conception of emotions and their significance in social interactions, 
which underlie the public-outward and the private-inward facets of social behavior in Confucian societies

(2) other-consciousness for the emergence of selfhood as necessary a condition as self-consciousness, both needing to be conceived together, with the role of metacognition as a central factor for the development of the social self.

‘Above, there are the old; below, there are the young.'
上有老，下有小


This reflects their awareness of responsibilities to be assumed by parents and by children. This also reflects the general case of Chinese family life in terms of responsibilities to perform

above a couple (or a self) there are parents to take care of, and below the couple (or the self) there are children to support. That is to say, they have responsibilities to support their parents and their children at the same time

the couple must try their best to
offer everything possible to satisfy their parents，materially and spiritually。

obey the parents for their happiness and not to lead them to be angry in terms of filial piety

In turn, the sons and daughters, younger brothers and sisters and younger brothers- and sisters-in-law are submissive to them in terms of love and respect

all the family members are instructed to follow the rule of living in harmony through showing respect for the old and showing love for the young in and outside of family.

Instructions in family life take very seriously such mis- behaviors as dishonesty, quarreling, stealing, indolence, and require all family members to prevent these. If any of these occurs, relevant members are seriously criticized (as if they were part of the one self!)

Thus, in the Chinese family-clan-based society, each individual is viewed as connected at least with two other generations. Thus, the three immediately connected generations, the father, the self (each individual), and the son, form the most basic family clan, with the self as its core.

The cultivation of personhood starting in the family through ‘the collective cultural voices (cultural forces) exert[ing] pressures intended to produce individual members (cultural products) who “fit” extant cultural ideals'


Confucianism and moral codes are the most important factor contributing to the cohesiveness of Chinese civilization (Stavrianos, 1971)

They focus on the establishment of a happy and well-organized society as cultural ideals.

Loyalty in interpersonal relationships is deemed as indispensable

The origin of this feeling of loyalty is the sentiment of grati- tude shown to parents by the children or the sentiment of gratitude shown for the favor of bearing them and bringing them up or the sentiment of love shown to the elder brother by the younger brother for his support in the early years of growth

(recall Xuanzi reminding me about connecting with mum on my birthday, its not my day, it should be a day for thanking my mum and dad for raising me!)

Confucian thinking on the development of FPFSL is concerned with the prevention of individuals' offending against their superiors for the social order

The philosopher You said, ‘There are few who, being filial and fraternal, are fond of offending against their superiors. There have been none, who, not liking to offend against their superiors, have been fond of stirring up confusion. The superior man bends his attention to what is radical. That being established, all practical courses naturally grow up. Filial piety and fraternal submission!—Are they not the root of all benevolent actions?' (The Confucian Analects, p. 65)

The structure of family relationships is seen as the political hierarchy of the state. Actually, a family is seen as a small state, and the state as a large family (guojia—the state family in its literal translation).

Family members and the sovereign of the state are assumed to take responsibility for each other.

The Confucian belief is that the proper governing of states is contingent on 
the cultivation of persons (personhood or selfhood) in families

They are expected to become sincere in their thoughts and rectified in their hearts in terms of ‘mutual loyalty to relationships' and observe the three fundamental principles

This loyalty is embodied in the design of the three principles of
benevolence, (loving others)
righteousness, and 
propriety,
which are interrelated requirements for individuals in Chinese cultural ideals.

Benevolence: one should do righteous deeds for one's neighbor in a proper, good, polite, and honorable manner

characteristic of taking responsibilities for others without directly requiring one's own rights. This is the essence of the Confucian construct of filial piety and fraternal submission

Loyalty in basic interpersonal relationships, incubated in family life in the form of FPFS, is deduced from the biological responsibilities and obligations an individual assumes for other blood-related members of the family


The Collection of Sages' Maxims (CSM)
major cultural-historical voices and establishes ‘the evaluative standards' of loyalty, against which trans- gression and violation of social normative maxims would arouse such emotions as guilt and shame (Ho et al., 2004)

The CSM is taken, in this respect, as performing the task of implementing Humboldt's idea of education on the individual level as the goal of humans, and for the purpose of broader humanity of reaching an ideal. 

The CSM can also be used to reveal psychical laws in V{\"{o}}lkerpsychologie by understanding ‘the historical forces that underlie collective life', and by ‘discovering the very nature of collective mental life' (Diriw{\"{a}}chter, 2004, p. 92).

History:
Ming Dynasty (1368–1644). It circulated widely among the people in the Qing Dynasty (1644–1911) and in the period of the Republic of China (1912–1949).

Content:
rhyming maxims, taken either from classical works, or directly from everyday vernacular expressions of common people, were so easy to read and memorize that their influence was no less than that of the classics of Confucius and Mencius

They had and still have a profound and lasting impact on China's politics, economy, ideological culture, people's customs and their psychological qualities (Guo {\&} Zhang, 1999; Wu, 1989; Yuan, 1988).

They are still often heard cited in daily communication today, orally or in written form, by common people as well as by intellectuals. For example, they are used as dicta, proverbs, mottos, and so on, or as themes in novels, movies, TV programs, news commentaries, textbooks, operas, paintings, calligraphies, couplets, posters, poems, songs, ads, and so on.

culture-bound nature of loyalty metaperception in the culturally constituted relational worlds

These maxims and embedded cognitive construals determine the shades of the characteristics of loyalty metaperception. The editions of the CSM used for this research were taken from the books annotated by T.-D. Yuan and by C.-Q. Wu and republished in 1988 and 1989, respectively.

Each cluster net has been made to reflect an actual integrative discourse for children's actual facilitated internalization of metacognition components in learning, and their actual development of metaperception in values or worldviews as a result.

Three Parts:
