2. IM: which is concerned with using the specific examples to illustrate the code of AM to family members.

3. RM: which serves as the more practicable requirement of people in the family for their daily behavior.

‘culturally expected, appropriate, “normative” behavior, at both collective and personal levels.' 

In RM, transgressions of personally interpreted ideals in social events and contexts are likely to be detected, and the meanings and consequences ascribed to the transgressions (including metaperception) can be reflected and typically represented

Eg:
AM: Harmony begets auspices, while disharmony begets perversities. (514)

