a happy and well- organized society in this world require harmony among people and result in their development of a relational self-conscious selfhood characteristic of other-consciousness

This harmony-seeking self–other consciousness is, first and foremost, developed among the four basic culturally significant family-based relations: father and son, elder brother and younger brother, family members with other villagers, husband and wife

The significance of this harmony-seeking lies in the need to support each other for shared interests or in terms of the convenience of neighbors available (non-family members)



(2) To Show Filial Piety to Parents and Respect for Elder Brothers (Filial Piety and Brotherly Love)

AM: The first thing we should do is to show filial piety to our parents, and show love and respect to our elder brothers, which is the radical to be established for practical courses to grow up. (5)

IM: A crow has the filial duty of feeding parents in return; a lamb has the knowledge to kneel down to express gratitude to its mother when sucking milk. (12)

RM: To keep in mind parents' remaining days and make them feel happy to show filial piety without delaying doing that till their portraits are engraved for the memorial ceremonies, as in case of Ding Lan; to kill an ox for sacrificial offerings to lay before the parents' tombs is not so good as to offer them chickens and pork when they are alive. (14)

CCMF 2: [making them feel happy by offering chickens {\&} pork when they are alive {\textgreater}|{\textless} engraving their portraits for memorial ceremonies by killing a cow for sacrificial offerings when they are dead].



The harmony building of one mind of two persons in the four most basic relationships is realized through the construct of filial piety and fraternal submission (FPFS).

particularly focusing on the prohibition of offending against superiors

(3) To Pay Adequate Attention to the Education of Children (Educating Children)

(1) To encourage parents to attach great importance to the education of children:

AM: If one is rich, but fails to instruct the children, the money and grain will certainly drain away; if one is a noble, but fails to instruct the children, his official costume and hat cannot be kept long. (389)

IM: If one is able to follow Mencius's mother's example and move house three times for her son's education, he can surely expect all his sons to be successful as Yanshan's five sons. (390)

RM: You should know that young children are worth instructing, and you should not say that they know nothing. (191)

