a significant interaction of justice sensitivity with pain vs. no-pain (b = .42, SE = 1.23, t = 2.31, p = .02), whereas the interaction of justice sensitivity with unfair vs. fair past behavior was not significant (b = 0.31, SE = 1.15, t = 1.49, p = .14).

a significant interaction (b =-.47, SE = 1.14, p = .02, R2 = .12). Simple slopes analysis showed that for those higher in Justice Sensitivity (?1 SD from the centered mean) there was a significant effect of condition on added points (b =-.45, SE = -1.11, p = .03), however for those lower on Justice Sen- sitivity (-1 SD from the centered mean) there was no comparable effect of condition on added points (b = .27, SE = 1.10, p = .19)

