psychology's efforts to account for human action have been hamstrung by the im- plausible attempt to sharply separate facts and values (2)

Individualism takes the individual to be the ultimate social reality and views the autonomous pursuit and satisfaction of individually defined ends as the ultimate goods in life (Bellah et al., 1985) (2)

The predominant understanding is that individuals pursue their chosen goods instrumentally, which means that they have subjectively predetermined ends, and they select the best strategies, techniques, and skills to attain those ends.

Self-determination theory (Ryan {\&} Deci 2000): three universal human needs: autonomy, competence, and social relatedness (2). 

These theories portray individuals as traders and relationships as quid pro quo interactions to be continued as long as the individuals believe they are getting a rea- sonably good relationship “deal.” (2)

