a good human life is inextricably tied to being a good person. This is one of the key reasons that eudaimonia cannot be studied in a value-neutral way. Aristotle also saw eudaimonia as inherently pleasant because excellent activity is pleasant. He distinguished noble pleasures (e.g., learning) from base plea- sures (e.g., gluttony), but he clearly saw both virtuous activity and a eudaimonic life as deeply pleasurable (6)

