are similar to what meditation practitioners refer to as “mental stickiness” and describes our nat- ural tendency to dedicate resources to an object of engagement to the extent that few resources remain to capture any other per- tinent environmental information until one is able to disengage (“let go”) and re-orient.












Over time, hypervigilance, avoidance, and disengagement delays can become habitual, contextually self- relevant, and highly crystalized sensory-affective-motor scripts and schemas that dictate tendencies toward behavior















...causally influencing and maintaining disordered affective states such as anxiety and depression. 








