@article{Brown2012,
annote = {
        Plato{\&}{\#}039;s Republic {\&} Eudaimonia: one of the central arguments in favour of being just
        

        

        

        
Glaucon and Adeimantus challenge Socrates to show that acting justly always makes one better off than acting unjustly (1)

        

        
Eudaimonia as "success":
This word is most commonly translated as {\&}{\#}039;happiness{\&}{\#}039;, though some have proposed {\&}{\#}039;flourishing{\&}{\#}039;. {\&}{\#}039;Success{\&}{\#}039; is a more natural rendering than the latter and less misleading than the former (1)

        

        
          

          
P: Socrates as the champion of eudaimonia as outcome of "virtous activity"

          

        
        

        
Does living justly make life more "profitable", or makes life "better"  G{\&}A question, but they only refer to eudaimonia once, obliquely... (1)

        

        
"Socrates seems to presuppose that questions about justice{\&}{\#}039;s value pertain to human beings who are pursuing success (358a1-3, taking makarios here to be a terminological variant of eudaimōn [cf. 354a1-2])" (2)

        

        
Thus, Plato combines living justly (morally) with human excellence {\&} success:

        

        
"...the best and most just is the most eudaimon, that this is the kingliest who is king over himself, that the worst and most unjust is the most wretched, and that this happens to be the one who is most tyrannical since he most tyrannizes both himself and his city?"" (3)

        

        
-- tyrannizes himself and his city: this is a personal and ethico-moral tyranny

        

        
Eudaimonia is a perfectly ordinary Greek word thatrefers nebulously, just as our word {\&}{\#}039;success{\&}{\#}039; does, to a mixture of good luck, noteworthy achievements, material comfort, and emotional well-being. So it is easily exchanged for "a good life," and what brings eudaimonia is easily called "advantageous" or "profitable." (3)

        

        

        

        The Socratic Conception (of Eudaimonia):
        

        

        

        
The argument, formed logically: 

        

        
1. The function of an X is what X alone or best does
2. The virtue/excellence of an X is what makes an X perform its function well (and be a good X), and the vice of an X is what makes an X perform its function badly (and be a bad X).
3. Living is the function of a (human) soul. 
4. Justice is the virtue/excellence of a human soul, and injustice its vice
5. So: A just soul lives well, and an unjust soul badly. 
6. Anyone who lives well is eudaimōn, and anyone who lives badly is wretched (athlios).
7. So: A just soul is eudaimōn, and an unjust one wretched. 8.It profits one not to be unhappy but to be happy. 
9. So: Injustice is never more profitable than justice.
(5)

        

        
"Living well" is crucial here:
          

          
Socrates identifies eudaimonia with justly living well (6).
Socrates frequently insists that being virtuous entails acting well which in turn entails being eudaimōn (6).

        

        
"And in this way, governed by 
        

        
          

        
        
          moderation
        
        
          

        
        

        , a household would be managed nobly [kalōs], and so would a city be governed, and so would everything else over which moderation rules. For with error removed and rightness in control, those disposed in this way necessarily 
        

        
          

        
        
          act nobly and well [kalōs kai eu] in every action,
        
        
          

        
        

         and those who act well are necessarily eudaimōn.
        

        

        

        

        

        P: Eudaimonia is virtous activity, not merely a list of good posessions (health and friendship etc) (8)
        

        

        

        
"If nothing is a good without being unconditionally beneficial (that is, beneficial in every circumstance), then, plausibly, health is not a good" (8).

        

        
          

          
virtous activity is a good and comes first before posessing goods:
        

        
"First, if eudaimonia is virtuous activity, then since virtuous activity requires at least some measure of health, one has good reason to value and pursue health just because one has good reason to value and pursue eudaimonia. Also, if eudaimonia is virtuous activity, it requires virtue, and if virtue requires evaluating positively things that have positive value, then eudaimonia can require positively evaluating health even if health is not to be seen as unconditionally beneficial and thereby good" (9)

        

        
Secondly, To say what eudaimonia is, one should not list all the necessary conditions for being eudaimōn. Such a list would include food, drink, and air, and a whole host of bacteria and enzymes.

        

        
Instead, one should say what makes a eudaimōn life eudaimōn and what serves as the practical goal for the sake of which a eudaimōn person should do everything he or she does (9)

        

        
nothing is good unless it benefits and nothing benefits unless it is used in a certain way. What makes a person eudaimōn, on this view, is activity of a certain sort and not the assets that the activity engages (9).
        

        

        

        
anyone who lives well is eudaimōn, and then it follows for Socrates in reply to G{\&}A:

        

        
(1) Justice is a virtue. 
(2) So: virtuous activity requires acting justly. 
(3) Eudaimonia is virtuous activity. 
(4) So: eudaimonia requires acting justly.
(10)

        

        
"Socrates{\&}{\#}039; strategy in the Republic is not to show that justice is a virtue on the assumption that eudaimonia is virtuous activity. It is to show that acting justly is or brings about more eudaimonia than acting otherwise, on the assumption that justice is a virtue that makes one good" (11).

        

        
          

          
The Adolescent Conception (of Eudaimonia):
        

        

        

        
Adeimantus raises the contention that private possessions are fundamentally important to eudaimonia:

        

        
Socrates has just finished explaining how the guardians will be situated in an ideal city. He says that they will live without private property—not even touching gold or silver—and with minimal sustenance, as soldiers in a camp with a common mess hall (416d-417b). 

        

        
          

          
This is almost like the coneption of the Buddha! 
        

        

        

        

        

        
Adeimantus worries about this (419a1-420a2): "What
defense will you offer, Socrates, if someone were to say that you don{\&}{\#}039;t make these men [sic] eudaimōn at all and that it{\&}{\#}039;s their own fault, since the city in truth belongs to them, yet they derive no good from it. Others own land, build fine big houses, acquire furnishing fitting for them, make their own private sacrifices to the gods, entertain guests, and also, of course, possess what you were talking about just now, gold and silver and all the things that are thought to belong to people who are blessed [makariois]. But one might well say that they are settled in the city like hired guards, doing nothing but watching over it." (13)

        

        
Adeimantus worries that the guardians of Socrates{\&}{\#}039; ideal city fail to be eudaimōn. But the charge is not that the guardians fail to act virtuously. Some other conception of eudaimonia is assumed.... (13)

        

        
(In book four, Socrates) politely and elaborately insists that his task is to design a city that is eudaimōn as a whole and not to design a city so that one or two particular classes in it are eudaimōn (420b-421c).

        

        
          

          
Is this an indication that there are "roles" for individuals in the creation of a republic? Some have access to eudaimonia, whereas others don{\&}{\#}039;t? 

          

        
        

        
Indeed, Socrates goes on to argue in Book 5: 
          

          

          

          
"If a
          

        
        
           guardian tries to become eudaimōn in such a way that he{\&}{\#}039;s no longer a guardian
        
        
          

         and isn{\&}{\#}039;t satisfied by a life that{\&}{\#}039;s measured, stable, and—as we say—best, but a foolish and adolescent view [anoētos te kai meirakiōdēs doxa] of eudaimonia seizes him and incites him to use his power to appropriate everything in the city for himself, he{\&}{\#}039;ll come to know that Hesiod was really wise when he said that {\&}{\#}039;the half is somehow more than the whole.{\&}{\#}039;"

        

        
          

          

          

        
        

        

        

        Here in book five Socrates rejects the adolescent conception of eudaimonia, asserting the foolishness of the guardian (whose role/function is to live moderately and be free from posessions so as to effectively guard the city) who would seek to possess goods as an "objective list theory" of eudaimonia would encourage.  This conception of eudaimonia is "adolescent", it involves attachment or grasping of objects and lack of understanding of the part that the individual plays in the realisation of the whole (the realisation of a just and virtuous "republic"

          

        
        

        
          

          
The Democritean Conception (of Eudaimonia): 

          

          

          

        Socrates{\&}{\#}039; crucial observation is that a soul, to the extent that it is filled with ever- growing appetitive desires, is more likely to experience conflicting and unsatisfiable desires and so less likely to do what it wants. That is why the most disordered soul filled with limitless appetites—the tyrannical soul—is least likely to do what it wants (17)

        

        
He then assumes that past manifestations of this inability occasion regret; present manifestations occasion feelings of poverty and frustration; and future manifestations occasion fear. These negative feelings then are summed up as wretchedness.

        

        
          

          
Doesn{\&}{\#}039;t this look a lot like the circular production of anxiety disorders, or the "reification of the dysfunctional narrative self" ? (Vago {\&} Silbersweig 2012: 3)

          

        
        

        
          

          
The just person experiences more pleasure than the unjust:
        

        
          

          

          

        
        

        
Socrates could generalize and conclude that vice correlates with psychological disorder which correlates with negative feelings, whereas virtue correlates with psychological order and the absence of negative feelings.
          

          

          

          
---This is psychological entropy! 

          

        
        

        
Eudaimonia might just be the presence of good feelings (such as pleasure) and the absence of bad feelings (such as pain). This subjectivist account might seem anachronistic, but it closely resembles the view that late antiquity attributes to Democritus, the atomist who was born some thirty years before Plato (17)
          

          

          

        
        

        
Democritus says that "the goal [telos, i.e., that for the sake of which one should do everything one does, i.e., eudaimonia] is good-spiritedness [euthumia], which is not the same pleasure, as some have misunderstood it to be, but that in which the soul continues in peace and in good balance, disturbed by no fear or superstition or any other passion (18).

        

        
Socrates explicitly rejects pleasure and good feelings as a guide to life and thereby rejects the view that eudaimonia is the presence of good feelings and absence of bad feelings (18-19).

        

        
Socrates: What about those who define the good as pleasure [cf. 505b5-6]? Does confusion fill them any less than it does the others [who define the good as knowledge, cf. 505b6-c5]? Or aren{\&}{\#}039;t they also forced to agree that there are bad pleasures?"

        

        
Socrates tries, among other things, to get Callicles to see that some pleasures are intrinsically shameful. More generally, on Socrates{\&}{\#}039; view, that something feels good for one does not mean that something is good for one (19-20).

        

        
And when we pursue the human good (eudaimonia), we pursue what is good for us and not merely what seems to be good for us (505d)

        

        

        

        So good feeling by itself is not enough. A good feeling must at least survive reflection as something good for us, and that requires some awareness of some good for us independent of good feelings (20)

        

        
P: subjective satisfaction—good feelings—come cheaply. Many different kinds of agents can get them, and all three parts of the human soul have their own pleasures (581c) (20).

        

        
Socrates maintains that if spirited and appetitive desires are indulged and are not held in check by countervailing commitments to what is genuinely good, they will grow stronger and more numerous (20)

        

        
"even the just person must continually prevent the many- headed beast of appetite from sprouting savage heads (589a-b; cf. 571b-572b)"

        

        
So Socrates{\&}{\#}039; moral psychology targets not only subjective satisfaction but also objective accounts of eudaimonia broader than the Socratic account, according to which eudaimonia is virtuous activity (21-22).

        

        

        

        

        

        

        

        

        

        

        

