Inclusion criteria, omong others: rated their partner as a significant source of social support, with a score of at least 7 on a scale from 1 (not a source of support) to 10 (a tremendous source of social support).
--{\textgreater} Four participants who were no longer with their partners by the end of the study were not included in the present analyses! (11725)

- two sessions:
Session 1: 
Participant arrived with her partner, pain threshold was determined using a double random staircase algorithim:

"if the previous response is above the chosen threshold, the next stimulus for that staircase is lowered, and if the rating is below the threshold, the next stimulus is increased. Stimuli from two staircases (with starting temperatures of 37 °C and 40 °C) were presented pseudorandomly to mask the rating–stimulus intensity relationship within a staircase. Stimulus temperatures on subsequent trials within a staircase were increased or decreased by increments between 1.6 °C and 0.2 °C, with smaller changes when the staircase crossed the threshold or reversed direction" 

“there are two different aspects of discomfort that people usually feel in response to the heat stimulations—one is how intense or strong the heat stimulation feels, and the other is how unpleasant or disturbing it is.” Participants were told that the present study was concerned with this second aspect of discomfort and that they should make their ratings based on how distressing or unpleasant they found the heat stimulations to be" 

Session 2: 
-Participants came to the session without their partners
-Two levels of heat stimulation: consisting of her threshold temperature (“moderate” pain) and her thres- hold temperature plus 1 °C (“high” pain) 
- 6 seconds of pain, followed by 7seconds break for 80 seconds
Three different conditions (counterbalanced)
- Four Photographs each of 1) attachment figures or controls 2) a chair or a3) a male stranger roughly matching partner's height, age, and weight. shown continuously for the 80s period
Pain rating made after each pain stimulus. 

H1: viewing pictures of the relationship partner (vs. control images) would reduce the threatening experience of physical pain, resulting in lower ratings of pain unpleasantness; 
H2: viewing pictures of the relationship partner (vs. control images) would reduce neural activity in regions previously associated with the unpleasantness of physical pain (dACC and anterior insula (25–27); 
H3: viewing pictures of the partner would lead to greater activity in the VMPFC, a region associated with safety signaling; and 
H4: greater VMPFC activity would be associated with reduced pain ratings and reduced activity in pain-related neural regions.
(11722)

Note: safety signaling versus reward reward processes
VMPFC also plays a role in reward experience. But, research on safety signaling and fear extinction processes
typically have yielded VMPFC activity without other reward-related regions such as the ventral striatum (11–14) and have shown that the ventral striatum is not needed for safety-signaling processes (33) (11722)

Is the experience of viewing attachment figures during pain more of a safety-signaling process or a rewarding experience? 

Can it be both???

Results:
H1:
as predicted, viewing partner pictures had pain-attenuating effects (self-report), and these effects were more pronounced during the high-pain trials.

H2: Pain-related neural activity?
As expected, participants showed significantly less activity in the dACC ROI and bilateral anterior insula ROI, while viewing partner vs. control pictures during the high-pain trials. Although in the right direction, these effects were not significant during the moderate- pain trials (P {\textgreater} 0.15). Thus, consistent with the self-report data, there was reduced activity in pain-related neural regions while viewing partner vs. control pictures during pain, and this effect was most pronounced in the high-pain trials (11723)

H3: Partner pictures and VMPFC?
Analysed partner versus stranger responses
Participants showed greater activity in theVMPFC in response to viewing partner vs. stranger pictures during pain. They also showed greater activity in the premotor cortex. There were no other regions that were more active during partner vs. stranger viewing.

Interestingly, consistent with the hypothesis that VMPFC ac-
tivity signals attachment-related safety, participants in longer- term relationships (categorized by the number of years together: 1=1 y or less; 2=1–2 y; up to 8=more than 7 y) showed greater activity in this same VMPFC cluster (r = 0.43, P {\textless} 0.05).

